title: A Randomized, Placebo-Controlled, Translational Study of ATH-1017 in Subjects With Mild to Moderate Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: This study is designed to evaluate treatment effects of ATH-1017 (fosgonimeton) in mild to moderate Alzheimer's subjects with a randomized treatment duration of 26-weeks.
description_detailed: This study is designed to assess the correlation of the functional translational biomarker P300 latency and change in ADAS-Cog11 induced by ATH-1017 therapy, over 26-week randomized, double-blind treatment.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: This was a multicenter, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, parallel-group, dose-ranging study comparing ATH-1017 40 milligrams per day (mg/day) and ATH-1017 70 mg/day with placebo in participants with a clinical diagnosis of mild to moderate Alzheimer's disease (AD).
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: The study was conducted at a total of 6 centers in Australia and 8 centers in the United States (US).

groups.title: Placebo
groups.description: Participants were randomized to receive placebo via subcutaneous (SC) injection once-daily (QD) preferably during daytime. The first SC injection of study drug was performed at site under supervision. The participant should withhold study drug administration on the day of subsequent clinic visits; study drug administration was done on site under supervision of site staff at these visits. Clinic visits took place on Day 1 and thereafter at Weeks 2, 6, 12, 16, 20, and 26, with a safety follow-up visit scheduled 4 weeks after completion of the double-blind period at Week 30

outcomeMeasures.title: Event-related Potential (ERP) P300 Latency at Baseline
outcomeMeasures.description: ERP P300 was a method of recording brain activity elicited by external stimuli, for example (e.g.), an oddball auditory stimulus, particularly of working memory access. The participant had to perform a task related to auditory stimuli in order to assess the P300 component (latency). The stimulus consisted of an oddball paradigm with 2 sound stimuli. Stimuli were presented through headphones and auditory stimulation for P300 was assessed in a recording lasting up to 10 minutes. It was calculated as the average across the pre-dose values at Baseline visit. Baseline was defined as Day 1.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Modified Intent-to-Treat (mITT) Population: included all randomized participants who took at least one dose of the study medication and who completed at least one ERP P300 Baseline assessment and/or one post-Baseline ERP P300 assessment.

outcomeMeasures.title: Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale-Cognitive Subscale (ADAS-Cog11) at Baseline
outcomeMeasures.description: The ADAS-Cog11 was designed to measure cognitive symptom change in participants with Alzheimer's Disease (AD) and consisted of 11 tasks. It was performed to evaluate the correlation of ERP P300 latency and cognition. The standard 11 items (and corresponding score range) were: word recall (0-10), commands (0-5), constructional praxis (0-5), naming objects and fingers (0-5), ideational praxis (0-5), orientation (0-8), word recognition (0-12), spoken language ability (0-5), comprehension of spoken language (0-5), word-finding difficulty (0-5), and remembering test instructions (0-5). The test included 7 performance items and 4 clinician-rated items. The ADAS-Cog11 total score was the sum of all 11 individual items, with a total score ranging from 0 (no impairment) to 70 (severe impairment). Higher scores indicated more severe cognitive impairment. Baseline was defined as Day 1.

drug: ATH-1017 (fosgonimeton) — small-molecule positive modulator of the HGF/MET system
explanation_target: Reason: The trial evaluates ATH-1017 (fosgonimeton) in mild–moderate Alzheimer’s disease over 26 weeks, so the intent is therapeutic treatment rather than a diagnostic only study. citeturn0search6

Act: ATH-1017 is the INN fosgonimeton and is described by the sponsor and peer-reviewed publications as a small-molecule positive modulator of the hepatocyte growth factor (HGF)/MET signaling system. It was developed as a regenerative/neurotrophic therapy aimed at restoring synaptic function and neuronal health. citeturn0search2turn0search5

Act (mechanism & evidence): Preclinical work and publications show fosgonimeton (and its active metabolite fosgo‑AM) promotes neurotrophic effects, synaptogenesis, and procognitive effects in models; a Phase 1 study showed pharmacodynamic brain effects (qEEG, ERP P300) consistent with target engagement and possible procognitive signal. citeturn0search1turn0search5

Act (trial context): The Phase 2/late-stage development included randomized 26‑week subcutaneous dosing to assess ERP P300 and clinical cognitive/functional endpoints. (Note: a mid/late-stage trial later reported not meeting its primary endpoint.) citeturn0search4turn0news12

Reflect: Classification rationale — because fosgonimeton is a small molecule designed to modulate a disease-relevant neurotrophic pathway (HGF/MET) with the stated goal of impacting neurodegeneration and synaptic repair (i.e., disease biology) rather than being solely a symptomatic cognitive enhancer or a neuropsychiatric symptomatic treatment, it fits the defined category 'disease-targeted small molecule.' There is some overlap in intent (procognitive effects), but the mechanism and development framing are disease-targeted rather than purely symptomatic. citeturn0search1turn0search5
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational drug ATH-1017 (fosgonimeton) is described and published as a small‑molecule positive modulator/agonist of the hepatocyte growth factor (HGF) / MET receptor signaling system — a canonical growth‑factor/receptor pathway. The program’s intent is disease‑targeted regenerative/neurotrophic activity (restore synaptic function, neurite outgrowth, neuroprotection), which maps most specifically to the CADRO category for Growth Factors and Hormones. citeturn0search2turn0search3

Act: Extracted key evidence from the literature and sponsor materials: (1) Fosgonimeton (ATH‑1017) is the INN for ATH‑1017 and is explicitly described as a positive modulator/agonist of HGF/MET. citeturn0search2turn0search5 (2) Preclinical studies show fosgo‑AM/fosgonimeton enhances MET phosphorylation, promotes downstream neurotrophic signaling, synaptogenesis, neurite outgrowth and procognitive effects in animal and cellular models. citeturn0search0turn0search3 (3) Clinical development (Phase 1 and the 26‑week ACT‑AD Phase 2 study) evaluated pharmacodynamic brain effects (qEEG, ERP P300) and cognitive/functional endpoints consistent with a disease‑targeted neurotrophic approach rather than a purely symptomatic agent. citeturn0search6turn0search1turn0search4

Reflect: The HGF/MET pathway is a growth‑factor signaling axis; CADRO category L (Growth Factors and Hormones) is the most specific fit. There is overlap with Synaptic Plasticity/Neuroprotection (CADRO M) because fosgonimeton’s downstream intent is to improve synaptic function, but the direct molecular target (HGF/MET) is a growth factor receptor — therefore L is preferred. If the trial had targeted multiple unrelated pathways, R) Multi‑target would be considered, but the description identifies a single primary pathway. Web sources used to support these points are cited above (Athira press releases and publications, PubMed preclinical and Phase‑1 reports, and product/mechanism summaries). citeturn0search0turn0search2turn0search3turn0search1
